<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
<a title="White Pigments" href="White_Pigments">White pigments</a> used in printing inks that do not let light pass through them, and are used for printing white, or for mixing with other colors to increase <a title="Opacity" href="Opacity">opacity</a> or lighten the color. The most opaque white pigment, <a title="Titanium Dioxide" href="Titanium_Dioxide">titanium dioxide</a>, is also called <a title="Cover White" href="Cover_White">cover white</a>. Other opaque white pigments include <a title="Zinc Sulfide" href="Zinc_Sulfide">zinc sulfide</a>, <a title="lithopones" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/lithopones">lithopones</a>, and zinc oxide. Frequently two or more of these pigments are mixed together to obtain the desired results. (See also <a title="Transparent Pigment" href="Transparent_Pigment">Transparent Pigment</a>.) 
</p>
